│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.        │
│ Understanding the Issue:\n\nThe SLP vectorizer is crashing with an          │
│ assertion failure in `isGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry()` at line 12474. │
│ The assertion expects that a gather node should have exactly one user       │
│ (`TEPtr->UserTreeIndices.size() == 1`), but the debugger shows that         │
│ `TEPtr->UserTreeIndices.size()` is 0 for the problematic tree               │
│ entry.\n\nThis tree entry (index 0) represents the bundle containing        │
│ `%cmp4.3 = icmp ne i32 %1, 0`, `%tobool10.not = icmp eq i32 %0, 0`,         │
│ `%cmp4.2 = icmp ne i32 %2, %conv3.2`, and `%cmp4.1 = icmp ne i32 %2,        │
│ %conv3.1`. It has state `NeedToGather` and contains 4 scalars.\n\nThe issue │
│ occurs during horizontal reduction analysis when the vectorizer tries to    │
│ analyze gather nodes for potential shuffling. The code assumes that all     │
│ gather nodes in `ValueToGatherNodes` should have exactly one user, but this │
│ assumption is violated.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n\nThe debug log shows │
│ that the vectorizer successfully identifies and schedules several           │
│ bundles:\n- A bundle of compares (`%cmp4.2`, `%cmp4.1`)\n- A bundle of      │
│ casts (`%conv3.2`, `%conv3.1`)\n- A bundle of xor operations (`%cmp2.2`,    │
│ `%cmp2.1`)\n\nHowever, the initial bundle containing 4 icmp instructions    │
│ (`%cmp4.3`, `%tobool10.not`, `%cmp4.2`, `%cmp4.1`) fails to schedule: \"We  │
│ are not able to schedule this bundle!\"\n\nThis unscheduled bundle becomes  │
│ a gather node (state `NeedToGather`) with no users in `UserTreeIndices`,    │
│ which violates the assumption in                                            │
│ `isGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry()`.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n\nThe  │
│ root cause is that the assertion in `isGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry()` │
│ is too strict. When a gather node cannot be scheduled (as in this case), it │
│ may legitimately have zero users in `UserTreeIndices`. The code that        │
│ populates `ValueToGatherNodes` includes such nodes, but the subsequent      │
│ analysis assumes all gather nodes must have exactly one user.\n\nLooking at │
│ the context around line 12474, the function is trying to find tree entries  │
│ that share gathered values to determine if they represent a shuffle         │
│ permutation. However, it doesn't handle the case where a gather node has no │
│ users, which can happen when the initial scheduling attempt fails.\n\n4.    │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe assertion should be relaxed to allow gather  │
│ nodes with zero users, since this is a valid state for unscheduled gather   │
│ nodes. The code should handle this case gracefully by skipping such nodes   │
│ rather than asserting.\n\n5. Conclusion:\n\nThe fix involves changing the   │
│ assertion to allow `UserTreeIndices.size() == 0` in addition to the         │
│ expected case of size 1. This handles the legitimate scenario where a       │
│ gather node cannot be scheduled and thus has no recorded users. The         │
│ surrounding code already has logic to handle empty `VToTEs` collections, so │
│ allowing zero-user gather nodes should not break the algorithm."})          │
